The '''Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) Men's Basketball Coach of the Year''' is a basketball award given to the men's basketball head coach in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] voted by members of the Atlantic Coast Sports Media Association as the most outstanding coach.<ref name="ACC"/> The award was first given following the [[1953<U+2013>54 Atlantic Coast Conference men's basketball|1953<U+2013>54 season]], the first year of the conference's existence, to [[Everett Case]] of [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|N.C. State]].<ref name="ACC"/>

[[Dean Smith]] of [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]] has won the most awards with eight wins. Thirteen other coaches have won the award more than once.<ref name="ACC"/>

Thirteen coaches have won ACC Coach of the Year in the same season that they have also won a National Coach of the Year Award;<ref name="ACC"/> of those, only [[Mike Krzyzewski]] of [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] and Dean Smith have achieved the feat three times. North Carolina has the most ACC Coach of the Year Awards with 11 while its [[Carolina<U+2013>Duke rivalry|in-state rival Duke]] is second with 10.<ref name="ACC"/> [[Frank McGuire]] is the only head coach to win the award twice at two different schools (North Carolina and [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina]]). Each of the original 1953&nbsp;ACC members have had at least one of their coaches win the award.<ref name="ACC"/>  [[Miami Hurricanes men's basketball|Miami (FL)]] and [[Boston College Eagles men's basketball|Boston College]] are the only schools without a winner.<ref name="ACC"/> As of 2010, the award has been given 57&nbsp;times in 57&nbsp;seasons.<ref name="ACC"/> Twenty-nine different coaches from eleven schools have received the award.<ref name="ACC"/>

